h3. Description
With JSON import, it's impossible to use wildcard in the selector. 

Consider a sample JSON file below and it's not possible to import the id and name of each array unless we can use "objects.ObjectFamily*" or in a similar format as the selector. 
{code}
{
  "objects": {
    "ObjectFamily::1": {
      "key": "1",
      "fields": {
        "id": "1",
        "name": "uno"
      }
    },
    "ObjectFamily::2": {
      "key": "2",
      "fields": {
        "id": "2",
        "name": "des"
      }
    },
    "ObjectFamily::3": {
      "key": "3",
      "fields": {
        "id": "3",
        "name": "tres"
      }
    },
  },
  "code": 0,
  "message": "Found: 3"
}
{code}

h3. Suggestion
* Support wildcard in the selector

At our main reference for Insight upgrades ([Preparing for Insight Version 8.4|https://documentation.mindville.com/insight/latest/preparing-for-insight-version-8-4-36953678.html]), there's no information about Insight's upgrade path restrictions.

If customers upgrade Insight from older versions, the following error can happen and block this plugin from being enabled:
{noformat}
Wrong version of Insight previously installed, you need to upgrade to the latest version of Insight 7.x.x before moving to Insight 8.x.x
{noformat}
We should add a warning there to avoid any unexpected behavior when upgrading Insight to 8.x.x versions, and also warn users as Insight is now bundled on Jira Service Management Data Center, so it will be automatically updated when upgrading Jira.

h2. Use case
We should make priority of clauses on IQL to minimize the CPU usage.
IQL:
{code:java}
object having inR() AND type = "Domain"
{code}

Should be in order:
{code:java}
type = "Domain" AND object having inR()
{code}

h2. Requirement
Auto fix the IQL when entered incorrectly
